Activities Committee doing enormous damage to 
every aspect of cultural life in LA. It was founded

28:47.199 --> 28:50.464
by the retired director of of ACNU at that time, but 
also a retired minister, Reverend A. A. Heist. And

28:58.697 --> 29:08.672
it was a small group of liberals that did not think 
about abolishing these committees, but were

28:58.697 --> 29:08.672
trying to defend the victims. When the hearings 
were held from then on, we tried to get the

29:11.076 --> 29:18.207
subpoenaed people together before they fell 
apart and began thinking their best friend was an

29:19.807 --> 29:25.874
informer. And help them get cheaper no-cost 
lawyers and develop public relations things that

29:27.976 --> 29:49.780
would improve community reaction to a UI hearing 
and maybe save jobs. The best example I can give you

29:51.380 --> 30:03.657
is in 1956 when the committee came to L.A. and 
subpoenaed 56 members of the Musicians' Union.

30:06.161 --> 30:07.984
There was always a reason. Of course, they claimed 
they were investigating a law. What was really

30:11.609 --> 30:20.982
going on is that there had been a Jim Crow local in 
Hollywood, and so the prime jobs went to whites.

30:22.042 --> 30:24.504
killed it down, then the black musicians could get 
in. And black and white unions, progressive

30:25.485 --> 30:30.830
unions, decided to have one local for all. And they 
brought in UAC to kill off the

30:31.791 --> 30:37.496
anti-discrimination group. When that happened, 
the Citizens Committee to Preserve American

30:38.857 --> 30:44.342
Freedoms had developed such a reputation. 
Citizens were served, we'll say, on a Thursday

30:45.723 --> 30:51.728
morning at 7 a.m.

30:53.108 --> 31:04.602
By that night, we had all 56 subpoenaed people in 
our office with an ACLU lawyer and some community

30:53.108 --> 31:04.602
support to talk how we could fight back. The 
creativity that comes out of these meetings was

31:06.164 --> 31:09.168
unbelievable. They found they had practically a 
full symphony orchestra amongst them except a

31:10.149 --> 31:16.016
piccolo player. They decided the night before the 
hearing they'd have a symphony concert made up

31:23.382 --> 31:26.625
entirely of subpoenaed musicians. And they did. 
They raised money to take a large hall seating

31:30.009 --> 31:41.041
sixteen hundred people, and they got a visiting 
cellist to come in and do a concerto. And they took

31:43.003 --> 31:51.972
out two or three thousand dollars worth of ads in 
the LA Times and all the

31:53.150 --> 32:06.662
The ad was a picture of an English horn, and then 
they had little Sherlock Holmes characters with

31:53.150 --> 32:06.662
spy glasses going around through the horns of the 
values, looking for spies. And the ad was

32:07.743 --> 32:15.469
entitled, Force and Violins, and then come to the 
concert. When that thing was over, not one

32:17.131 --> 32:22.195
musician lost their job. Dorothy Chandler, wife 
of the editor of the LA Times, the main patron of the

32:22.748 --> 32:36.902
LA Symphony, her four favorite musicians, 
including her first oboist or something, were

32:22.748 --> 32:36.902
called. And she defended them all, wouldn't allow 
any of them to be fired, because they were just fine

32:38.023 --> 32:43.529
musicians.

32:46.291 --> 32:47.453
That's your question. It was founded in 1952. I was 
blacklisted. I guess that's the word. How did you

32:55.931 --> 32:58.694
find out that you were blacklisted? Well, you get 
instant notice of that from the public that

32:58.714 --> 33:05.260
afternoon. It was in August of 28. For two months, 
the LA Times, Herald, all of them were just filled

33:10.966 --> 33:17.553
with these wild and scary headlines. You would 
sometimes be interested in seeing a scrapbook of

33:18.794 --> 33:22.978
two months of headlines. Every day, my picture, my 
name, everything was all over the papers. And I

33:30.829 --> 33:34.134
became totally unemployable. The Citizens 
Committee was founded in September of 52, but I had

33:35.075 --> 33:40.542
no connection with it. I went until the spring of 53 
without any kind of a job.

33:51.865 --> 33:57.471
was called before the committee as a school 
teacher. She taught social studies for 13 years in

33:57.511 --> 34:01.956
the LA City school system. Very, very popular, 
very successful teacher. And she was fired

34:07.441 --> 34:15.750
because she refused to answer questions of the 
committee on the grounds of husband-wife

34:07.441 --> 34:15.750
privilege conversations. It was guilt by me, 
through me, that they got her out. So we had no

34:19.814 --> 34:21.636
income coming in. Finally, in June of 53, a

34:23.050 --> 34:50.475
Quaker family in Pasadena that owned a large 
department store

34:23.050 --> 34:50.475
called me and met me privately and arranged for me 
to be the sole janitor on a three-story department

34:23.050 --> 34:50.475
store that they had, coming in an hour after the 
store closed because they didn't think anyone

34:23.050 --> 34:50.475
should see me coming. and I was not to tell anybody 
that I was working for them. And they gave me a

34:55.477 --> 35:06.729
dollar an hour from six thirty in the night until 
four thirty in the morning to clean three, three

34:55.477 --> 35:06.729
floor hardwood departments. All the showcases, 
sixteen toilets, vacuuming, the work. Horrible,

35:13.536 --> 35:16.078
horrible, horrible experience for me. The peak of 
my, my job at those When I was fired, my job in

35:19.058 --> 35:22.423
today's money was around $65,000. Yeah. And then 
suddenly I'm dead. I was getting a buck an hour to be

35:27.470 --> 35:30.715
a janitor. At that point. Why'd they hire you? 
Quaker family. Yeah. Quakers were the best.

35:39.848 --> 35:48.441
Robert Hutchins, Hallert Hoffman, the son of Paul 
Geoff, an Eisenhower's

35:39.848 --> 35:48.441
cabinet member. Robert Hutchins of the former 
Chicago heard about me and came, they were active

35:48.995 --> 36:00.033
in the AFSC in Pasadena, and they came and helped 
me.

36:02.877 --> 36:08.787
The YMCA of Hollywood refused to let my children go 
to summer camp that first summer. My Sunday school

36:10.730 --> 36:12.673
superintendent came He was the director of the 
YMCA, but he had been my assistant director. My

36:20.047 --> 36:22.649
kids had gone every year for four years or 
whatever. He came and said, they've been trying

36:23.530 --> 36:28.975
and trying, and he finally got a compromise. They 
let my kids come if my wife and I would not bring them

36:28.995 --> 36:44.550
to the Y on Saturday morning, and if we would not 
come up the following Sunday to the campsite in the

36:28.995 --> 36:44.550
mountains for chapel services. And if I'd get a 
private doctor to check them over, because the

36:45.728 --> 36:54.476
doctor at the Y said he would not see my kids. At that 
point, the Quakers called me and offered me free

36:56.618 --> 37:03.865
family camp.

37:07.028 --> 37:09.991
Very good attitude, the Quakers and Pasadena at 
that time. I'm not giving you a card, but I'm just

37:10.432 --> 37:13.495
saying Quakers. Nixon was a Quaker. Anyway,

37:15.310 --> 37:42.938
in the summer of 1953, Reverend Heist and the new 
director of ACNU, Easton Monroe,

37:15.310 --> 37:42.938
and two or three other people, members of that 
Citizens Committee, came to me and said they

37:15.310 --> 37:42.938
wanted me to become the secretary of the Citizens 
Committee to Preserve American to help defend the

37:43.745 --> 37:45.787
victims of UAC. And I turned him down cold. Said 
that anything I would touch, I'd destroy. The

37:53.215 --> 37:59.883
committee could never be effective if I were any 
way associated with it. And they argued exactly

38:02.105 --> 38:04.208
the opposite.

38:07.531 --> 38:11.035
And took some arguing, because I really felt that. 
was only when the ACLU director in this miniature

38:11.622 --> 38:22.094
really said they knew that my organizing skills 
would be just wonderful for it. And they also felt

38:23.735 --> 38:30.563
that nobody knows what is a victim of UI, except the 
victim of UI. Fight back. So I went to work for them.

38:35.909 --> 38:38.592
And that became my job. Within two years, we turned 
it from just the victims to a long-range campaign

38:38.875 --> 38:44.283
to abolish. And by 1960, we

38:46.105 --> 38:53.696
set up a national committee to abolish. And in 
1958,

38:55.238 --> 39:06.233
my reputation, the committee's reputation, but 
my personal reputation of being able to go into any

38:55.238 --> 39:06.233
town

39:09.672 --> 39:14.359
and organized subpoenaed people into a fight 
back. Became nationally known. I was flying to

39:16.282 --> 39:27.579
Chicago, flying to Boston, flying to San 
Francisco, Gary, Indiana, and 20 I got a call to

39:16.282 --> 39:27.579
come down to Atlanta. I'd never been in the South. 
And I went down there to circulate a petition among

39:30.304 --> 39:37.755
church people, not to abolish UAC, but to keep it 
out of the South. arguing that it was hard enough to

39:38.528 --> 39:48.702
have dialogue between black and white without

39:38.528 --> 39:48.702
having one side labeled a communist. Sure. Long 
answer, that's the answer. That committee lasted

39:53.888 --> 40:00.177
up until we formed the National Committee to 
Avalanche Your Act. And is that when, when you went

40:00.197 --> 40:07.827
to Atlanta, is that when you were cited for 
contempt of court? August of 58. It was at that

40:11.652 --> 40:14.616
time, we never knew how it happened. I did not know I 
was going down to Atlanta until the day before. Got

40:18.681 --> 40:26.030
a telegram, meet people in Atlanta, worked with 
Martin Luther King Sr. and others. And I made a

40:28.013 --> 40:36.463
plane reservation, flew down, and it had been a 
minute after I checked into the hotel where they

40:28.013 --> 40:36.463
told me to come. I was subpoenaed to appear before 
UI. We thought it was just the Un-American

40:40.173 --> 40:45.621
Activities Committee following me, following 
everybody, everywhere. And we learned just this

40:47.143 --> 40:59.282
last year that they had me under, they had eight 
agents following me from seven in the morning till

40:47.143 --> 40:59.282
ten at night, all my conversations wiretapped, 
everything. They knew everything about where I

40:59.743 --> 41:05.792
was going, what I was doing, and were trying to 
disrupt my work. The real disruption didn't begin

41:06.397 --> 41:09.261
until the early 60s. The COINTELPRO of FBI didn't 
begin until 56. In Georgia, it was 58. At any rate, I

41:14.887 --> 41:20.034
made a—ACID wanted a witness. They'd been trying 
for five years to get somebody who would not claim

41:21.015 --> 41:30.166
the privilege of the Fifth Amendment to make a 
First Amendment challenge. And I had been

41:30.286 --> 41:31.288
looking. No one was willing to do it because I was 
almost sure to go to jail. we all felt that somebody

41:36.923 --> 41:38.886
should do it. As a matter of conscience, we wanted 
the issue raised. And there were some inklings in

41:43.894 --> 42:02.562
the dicta of some of the Warren Court decisions 
that implied that they might consider taking on

41:43.894 --> 42:02.562
the Un-American Activities Committee on First 
Amendment grounds.

42:02.582 --> 42:02.762
Go ahead. And so you were subpoenaed in front of 
HUAC. Now, originally, you were down there to help

42:06.525 --> 42:19.380
with the beginnings of the civil rights program, 
correct?

42:19.400 --> 42:30.072
First time I ever went to Georgia, first time I ever 
went to the South, was when I came down in July of 58

42:19.400 --> 42:30.072
and was subpoenaed. The civil rights thing in 
Montgomery had begun in 54. Yeah, right. From then

42:35.142 --> 42:54.065
on, I became involved in the Civil Rights program 
in the South, but all in connection with the

42:35.142 --> 42:54.065
way the Un-American Activities Committee was 
being used as a bulwark for segregation. Right,

42:54.085 --> 42:55.406
right. Martin King,

42:55.427 --> 43:04.137
there's a picture of us together there, that's at 
Morehouse College. After the court decision came

43:04.825 --> 43:20.165
down and we'd exhausted our appeals and we were 
going to jail, he and Coretta King had a reception

43:04.825 --> 43:20.165
for Carl and me at Morehouse College the night 
before we went to jail. And 400 black leaders were

43:21.186 --> 43:25.071
sat out there to honor us as we went to jail. And

43:26.673 --> 43:34.123
I don't think I've ever seen the newspaper 
clipping on it. because I went right into jail. But

43:38.670 --> 43:44.175
his statement was extremely important 
historically. He said that we're honoring these

43:44.195 --> 43:46.677
men. He said, these men are going to jail for us.

43:53.362 --> 44:02.390
We will never achieve peaceable integration in 
the South until the Un-American Activities

43:53.362 --> 44:02.390
Committee has been abolished. And then we went on 
to jail. When

44:06.284 --> 44:20.400
I was in jail, he and Reinhold Niebuhr and others 
started a petition for clemency to get us out,

44:06.284 --> 44:20.400
which Kennedy denied while we were in. On what 
grounds?

44:24.985 --> 44:26.066
Kennedy was no good.

44:30.832 --> 44:33.895
The Secretary of the World Council of Churches 
Chicago was his name, took this petition,

44:35.512 --> 44:46.104
launched by Martin Luther King, Jr., Reinhold 
Niebuhr, A.J. Muste, Dean John Bennett, Union

44:46.124 --> 44:53.292
Theological Seminary, really top, top people. 
Howard Schomer, S-C-H-O-M-E-R, your record will

44:53.733 --> 45:01.141
be the first time it's accurate. He was secretary 
of the World Council of Churches. He was on his way

45:03.929 --> 45:07.934
to New Delhi for a World Church Conference. He 
delayed it to deliver these 3,500 names to

45:07.954 --> 45:12.721
President Kennedy. And when he went down there to 
see him, Kennedy would not even meet the

45:13.883 --> 45:21.473
delegation, turned it over to his pardon 
attorney, who immediately rejected it. And of

45:24.016 --> 45:28.342
course, we now know the records, you see. The 
moment I went into jail, The FBI's whole apparatus

45:32.583 --> 45:36.727
on me went into prison with me. They just sent me, 
two months ago, every letter that I wrote and every

45:36.747 --> 45:47.797
letter I received while I was in prison. These were 
all part of the file. They had surveillance on me.

45:51.441 --> 46:01.290
And we were moved around from prison to prison to 
prison as terrible harassment as political

45:51.441 --> 46:01.290
prisoners.

46:03.211 --> 46:13.885
The pressure on the Kennedys, Bobby and Jack, from 
the FBI was enormous there. Why do you think that

46:14.226 --> 46:15.227
was? I think Hoover, first of all, Hoover had no 
real mandate to do what he was doing. It was just

46:27.143 --> 46:32.290
something sort of an accretion, a collection of 
power given to him at the budget hearings each

46:34.953 --> 46:42.120
year, beginning with Harlan Stone back in 1924 
through Roosevelt.

46:46.665 --> 47:01.720
And Hoover had adverse information on the sex and 
the financial,

46:46.665 --> 47:01.720
every kind of dealing that would either be 
illegal, or corrupt, or immoral, or bad PR. He had

47:10.055 --> 47:11.016
it on them all. When I, the decision came down in the 
60th term of the court, beginning of 58, take your

47:11.337 --> 47:29.040
time, February 28th, my attorneys, Roland Watts, 
the National ACNU, and Nanette Dembitz, who was

47:30.725 --> 47:43.114
The niece of Justice Brandeis, who was writing the 
briefs on my case, they filed appeal after appeal

47:30.725 --> 47:43.114
to delay my jailing as long as they could.

